This whole anti-vista thing is a joke. On Nov 7th, I will have been using
Vista Ultimate for a year, and it has been an absolute joy - not without any
trials and tribulations (mostly x64 issues), but I've certainly never looked
back. That said, I'd never recommend that anyone upgrade to it. But as
people buy new machines, they should get Vista included.

Back on-topic, DX10 will never be available on XP. Even if a 3rd party could
develop a wrapper (possible perhaps) and that performance was reasonable
(not sure), there is certainly no way MS are going to allow it. DX10 is one
of the carrots to encourage earlier adoption of Vista and it is the hook
that caught most gamers who have bothered to upgrade. MS are simply not
going to allow DX10 to run on XP. I doubt they have a legal case; more
likely they will change the way either XP of DX10 works, such that it will
break the 3rd-party wrapper.

By the time said 3rd parties can react, Vista adoption will be widespread
and DX10+XP will be a niche market.

That said, from what I have seen of DX10, if you have a top end gfx card, it
can make some thigs look really purdy... but the improvement is
incremental... People agree it looks better and some more complex things can
be renders more 'cheaply' but there is no 'Wow!' factor.

Bioshock looked pretty damn good on DX9 anyway. Besides, apart from the
first few stages, who stopped long enough to to even notice the scenery... I
was too busy fightly splicers.
