I had Vista on my machine back in (I think) March. It came with the machine
so I didn't complain too much. In the end I went back to XP in a space of
around 2 months. My reasons were many and were mostly to to with many of my
apps not working properly, some of the bugs in Vista (Like the file copying
one - when I tried to copy too many files it would hang for a while, white
screen and tell me explorer was being restarted with the copy operation
having not been carried out) and the reduced functionality (Stripped down
defragger, No hotmail in the new email client).

Once I 'downgraded' after having slipstreamed my old XP disk, I was suprised
to find big performance gains in all of my games, including certain
Microsoft ones that claim they run better under Vista. A case in point being
the new 'Acceleration Pack' for MS's FSX flight sim. On their blog site they
claim a 12% increase in framerate under Direct-X10 compared to Direct-X9.
This is ok, until someone asked which Direct-X 9 were they measuring? XP or
Vista? The response was 'Vista' and they conceded that under XP the frame
rates were on par with the Vista Direct-X10 version. To me it seems what
Direct-X10 gives in one hand, Vista takes from the other.

I will not go back to Vista just yet, even though I have an nVidia GTX8800
in my system which is Direct-X10 capable. I might change eventually, but all
the current evidence and my own experiences force me away from that option.

RobP
